  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 14:4-5",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Chronicles 14:4-5",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He commanded Judah to seek the Lord ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— By his royal edicts he commanded them to worship God, and him only. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And to do the law, and the commandment — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To observe all divine institutions, which many had neglected, and to practise all that the law of Moses required of them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the kingdom was quiet before him — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Though, it is probable, they were much in love with their idols, and very loath to part with them; yet the convictions of their consciences sided with the commands of Asa, and they could not, for shame, but comply with them. They that have power in their hands, and will use it vigorously for the suppression of profaneness, and the reformation of manners, will, in general, not meet with so much difficulty and opposition as, perhaps, they might expect. Vice is a mean and base thing, and carries its own shame and condemnation on the face of it; while virtue has always reason enough on its side to make ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "iniquity stop her mouth, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 107:42",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
